excel_data.What are the key findings of the study (:
Validity parity with Probe on test problems (≈95–99% across domains).
Shorter plans: Up to 13.5% fewer steps (Teriyaki-NO-MACRO vs Probe).
Action streaming: Average wait time −61.2%; response-time std −95.6% vs Probe.
Transfer result: MACRO→NO-MACRO transfer rapidly reached high validity (95.2% after 1k), enabling early stopping
excel_data.Author‑reported limitations: Domain-specific training; slower end-to-end planning than Probe (with GPT-3); context window constraints; difficulty with mathematical/numerical/temporal planning.
excel_data.Reviewer‑identified limitations / threat: Dependence on proprietary GPT-3 “davinci” API (deprecation risk), timing comparisons acknowledged as not directly fair due to cloud queuing, and also ( as shown in the paper) the NSAI planner did not perform that well against other domain symbolic planners. Also, the neuro-symbolic planner would probably not perform well on out of domain provided tasks to plan for.

EDITED:
tl;dr - documentation and environmental versioning not adequate to allow for reproduciton of results

One of the datasets required to reproduce the evaluation from this study ( the HighD dataset ) is not open source / publicly available for download. Access to the dataset has been requested. Reviewer will redo this data extraction review (if and when) the required evaluation has been made accessible i.e. once our request for access is approved. 

EDIT: ----------------------------
After gaining access to the HighD dataset and saving it into our local data/highd/ path, we were still unable to reproduce the paper’s results due to environment fragility and undocumented steps. Specifically, the codebase depends on manual patches to PySwip (adding a non-standard Prolog.reconsult() method and changing PL_version --> PL_version_info for SWI-Prolog 9.0.4). In our HPC/conda setup, even with SWI-Prolog correctly installed and PySwip importable, evaluation and training failed wherever reconsult() was called (e.g., in train.py and reproduce/evaluate.py), raising AttributeError: 'Prolog' object has no attribute 'reconsult'. Additional headless issues from Pygame/ALSA appeared but were mitigated with SDL_* env vars; however, the PySwip mismatch remained a hard blocker. Because the repository provides only a minimal, unpinned requirements.txt and no container/conda spec to unify SWI-Prolog+PySwip ABI versions, we could not execute the full 50-episode evaluation protocol despite having the required HighD data.

title: Learning for Long-Horizon Planning via Neuro-Symbolic Abductive Imitation
author: Shao, Jie-Jing and Hao, Hao-Ran and Yang, Xiao-Wen and Yu-Feng, Li
abstract: Recent learning-to-imitation methods have shown promising results in planning via imitating within the observation-action space. However, their ability in open environments remains constrained, particularly in long-horizon tasks. In contrast, traditional symbolic planning excels in long-horizon tasks through logical reasoning over human-defined symbolic spaces but struggles to handle observations beyond symbolic states, such as high-dimensional visual inputs encountered in real-world scenarios. In this work, we draw inspiration from abductive learning and introduce a novel framework 𝐀B ductive 𝐈 mitation 𝐋 earning (ABIL) that integrates the benefits of data-driven learning and symbolic-based reasoning, enabling long-horizon planning. Specifically, we employ abductive reasoning to understand the demonstrations in symbolic space and design the principles of sequential consistency to resolve the conflicts between perception and reasoning. ABIL generates predicate candidates to facilitate the perception from raw observations to symbolic space without laborious predicate annotations, providing a groundwork for symbolic planning. With the symbolic understanding, we further develop a policy ensemble whose base policies are built with different logical objectives and managed through symbolic reasoning. Experiments show that our proposal successfully understands the observations with the task-relevant symbolics to assist the imitation learning. Importantly, ABIL demonstrates significantly improved data efficiency and generalization across various long-horizon tasks, highlighting it as a promising solution for long-horizon planning. Project website: \url https://www.lamda.nju.edu.cn/shaojj/KDD25\_{A}{B}{I}L/ .

excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items: Too many pieces are frozen to an ecosystem that no longer exists on modern GPUs. The repo’s environment.yml hard-pins Python 3.6, CUDA 10.0, cuDNN 7.x, TensorFlow-1.13, and PyTorch-1.1—packages that are gone from today’s conda channels and incompatible with A100 nodes. Trying to “modernize in place” then collides with a second constraint: the paper’s metrics rely on TF-1 (which needs ≤Python 3.7), while training reasonably requires a much newer PyTorch/CUDA; mixing those in a single env triggers unsatisfiable solves and runtime errors (NumPy/OpenBLAS crashes, ABI mismatches). On the data side, one official MPI3D link is dead, and the alternative requires extra steps (label injection) not automated in the repo; the preprocessing bundle (preprocessing.zip with scripts/k-means pickles) isn’t publicly hosted, so parts of the pipeline can’t run end-to-end. In short, obsolete dependencies, hardware/driver incompatibilities, a non-portable metrics toolchain, and missing/decayed data resources collectively block a faithful reproduction.

This was particularly disappointing to see as we ( the annotators for this survey ) spent days on gathering all of the artefacts necessary ( code, model weights, dataset etc.), setting up the environment properly and generating the wrapper necessary to run the evaluation bash scripts on Zaratan with the 8 GPU's required ( but not specified in the documentation - another issue with reproduction). Additionally, the repo provides a dockerfile for docker reproduction, but reproduction using a containerised environment requires apptainer ( as 8 GPU's are needed and most HPC's do not give root access which docker requires) and the docker script ( upon further inspection) is does not provide access points required to reproduce the experiment, it is just a framework shell that sets up the dependencies. So, tl;dr, this failed reproduction was particularly disappointing as it seemed ( from the outside) that the authors provided everything required but upon further inspection, it is clear that the framework testing scripts have never been tested ( apart from possibly on the authors machine ) and the containerized environment offered is just a shell that would not allow for the reproduction of experimental results.

note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: A Neural Lambda Calculus: Neurosymbolic AI meets the foundations of computing and functional programming
excel_data.Study design / paper type ( dataset pape: Framework / algorithmic study (Neuro‑Symbolic integration applied to lambda calculus)
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: The paper presents a neurosymbolic framework that combines neural networks with lambda-calculus reduction rules to learn and execute functional programming operations. It reports quantitative evaluation on one-step and full computation reduction tasks, demonstrating high accuracy on synthetic lambda-term datasets.
excel_data.Compute/hardware reported: GPU  (specify type below e.g., A100, V100), CPU only, Memory / batch size reported
excel_data.Notes on reproduction:
Reproducing the results required manual code modifications. In utils.py, the timeout decorator was refactored for cross-platform safety, and in char_sp.py, all logger.error(..., e) calls were replaced with logger.error(..., exc_info=True) to properly log exceptions.

Despite these changes, certain expressions in char_sp.py consistently raise UnboundLocalError due to uninitialized local variables (infix) and incomplete handling of edge cases during expression generation. This prevents the full execution of the data generation and training pipeline. Consequently, although the code and data are publicly available, the reported results from the paper cannot be exactly reproduced because of persistent logical errors and fragile control flow in the codebase.

excel_data.Datasets used for Evaluation: Synthetic / Procedural, Toy logical datasets (symbolic math, rule chains), Custom dataset (introduced in paper)
excel_data.Baselines / ablations compared against: Ablation on operator counts, model architecture variations (encoder/decoder layers, attention heads)
excel_data.Notes on metric computation quirks (Any: Outputs are procedurally generated symbolic expressions; Exact Match metric used. Some metrics may vary due to non-deterministic generation and OS-dependent code execution issues.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items: Required multiple edits to run the code on Windows (e.g., utils.py timeout decorator, char_sp.py logger changes). Even after modifications, some tasks produce recurring errors (UnboundLocalError) and outputs diverge from the paper’s reported results. Full reproduction across OS/environments is not currently possible. Follow-up: codebase needs fixes for cross-platform compatibility and proper handling of generated expressions to achieve reproducibility.

This paper details a Neuro-Symbolic Framework that merges deep learning with symbolic reasoning via Semantic-Based Regularization to enhance forest inventory tasks. This undocumented geospatial pipeline acts as a major technical barrier, forcing any user to rebuild a specialized data preprocessing system from the ground up.

Although the documentation and codebase are thorough, I still encountered various execution challenges that required significant time and effort to address before we could successfully execute the code.

After about 4 hours of addressing system- and code-level issues, I was still unable to successfully run the code. The codebase could not be executed successfully as provided, despite substantial corrective efforts.

Some examples of such issues: 
+ Issue 1:Segmentation fault caused by OpenBLAS thread initialization. Workaround: "import os; os.environ['OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS'] = '1'"
+ Issue 2: Segmentation fault related to package dependency. Workaround: "pip install overrides==3.1.0"
+ Issue 3: PyCapsule_Import could not import module "datetime". Workaround: add "import os; os.environ['OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS'] = '1'" to the processing file.
+ Issue 4: Dataset name mismatch during preprocessing steps. Solution: requires manual modification of multiple configuration and script files.
+ Issue 5: Input type (torch.cuda.FloatTensor) and weight type (torch.FloatTensor) should be the same. Solution: manual debugging, bug-tracing, and code editing across multiple files in the codebase, which were time-consuming to hard trace and fix.

Upgrading to a CUDA 11.8-compatible PyTorch (e.g., 1.12+) would likely require retraining the provided checkpoints, as they were saved with PyTorch 1.0.1 and may not be compatible with newer versions. The codebase targets an older software stack that cannot be replicated without substantial dependency updates, model architecture changes, or access to the original training environment. title: Neural-Symbolic Models for Logical Queries on Knowledge Graphs
note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: Neural-Symbolic Models for Logical Queries on Knowledge Graphs
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: propose Graph Neural Network Query Executor (GNNQE), a neural-symbolic model that enjoys the advantages of both worlds. GNN-QE decomposes a complex FOL query into relation projections and logical operations over fuzzy sets, which provides interpretability for intermediate variables. To reason about the missing links, GNN-QE adapts a graph neural network from knowledge graph completion to execute the relation projections, and models the logical operations with product fuzzy logic.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
MISSING ARTIFACTS: the authors do not provide the pretrained GNN-QE model checkpoints used for all reported results and, in addition, the released codebase shows unresolved reliability and usability issues. Specifically, multiple open GitHub issues report (1) checkpoint loading bugs caused by TorchDrug–PyTorch incompatibilities (e.g., checkpoint['model']['graph'] expected as a tensor but stored as graph.Graph, only workaround being to downgrade PyTorch), (2) training runs that hang or stall for many hours or appear stuck at “Evaluate on valid” even after long epochs, with no official fix or clear guidance from the authors, and (3) behavior that depends on silently guessing compatible library versions. The README provides only minimal installation and a single python script/run.py -c config/fb15k237.yaml --gpus [0] usage example, with no explicit training procedure, no end-to-end reproduction instructions, and a non-pinned, underspecified requirements.txt, forcing substantial guesswork on dependency versions. The missing pretrained checkpoints makes this work not reproducible and the additional unresolved reported issues, and sparse documentation/ versioning hinders us and further prevents us from reliably loading and evaluating the authors’ models or even deterministically retraining them, and therefore we exclude this paper from our evaluation-only reproducibility study.

This paper has been cited 129 times from their MLR press release and to hte best of my knowledge ( and after doing a look through the papers that cite it), I cannot find anyone who has reproduced their work / anyone who uses their code / system in their work. Alot of the citations for this work is just used as background information which is concerning.

title: LEVERAGING LLMS FOR HYPOTHETICAL DEDUCTION IN LOGICAL INFERENCE: A NEURO-SYMBOLIC APPROACH
note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: LEVERAGING LLMS FOR HYPOTHETICAL DEDUCTION IN LOGICAL INFERENCE: A NEURO-SYMBOLIC APPROACH
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: introduce LINA, a LLM-driven neuro-symbolic approach for faithful logical reasoning.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items: CODEBASE MALFORMED AND BROKEN: The released artifacts are fundamentally incomplete and internally inconsistent. The core LLM interface functions (LLM_response, LLM_response_multi) in experiments/manual.py are left as empty placeholders, and the README simply instructs users to “fill” them, without specifying a reference implementation, API contract, or even the expected return structure beyond a vague “openai choices list.” This means the central component that actually defines the model’s behavior is not provided and must be re-designed by the user, which invalidates any claim of faithful reproduction of the authors’ results. In addition, the experiment scripts themselves are structurally broken: they contain hard-coded Windows-style paths (e.g. .\datasets\\reclor\\npy\\val.npy) that are not portable to a standard Linux HPC environment; they implement arbitrary sample caps (e.g. 50–100 examples) directly in the experiment code, which prevents full-dataset evaluation unless the user edits the core scripts; and they mishandle the types and formats returned by the LLM functions (e.g. expecting lists where strings are returned, wrong dataset keys such as 'choices' vs 'answers'), causing direct baselines and CoT-SC runs to crash or silently produce invalid outputs. Because (1) the key LLM behavior is unspecified and must be written by the user, (2) the released code contains logic and path errors that prevent out-of-the-box execution on standard infrastructure, and (3) there is no authoritative, working reference implementation that ties the prompts, model calls, and evaluation together, the paper’s reported results cannot be independently and faithfully reproduced from the public artifacts.

title: SATYRN: A Platform for Analytics Augmented Generation
note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: SATYRN: A Platform for Analytics Augmented Generation
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: propose an approach that uses the analysis of structured data to generate fact sets that are used to guide generation in much the same way that retrieved documents are used in RAG.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
We cloned the public Satyrn repository, created the satyrn conda environment as described in the README, and installed all dependencies. During our attempts to reproduce the results, we had to fix several code and configuration issues just to get the architecture to initialize: we added the repo root to sys.path so core can be imported, changed our harness to read rings via app.rings because the documented /api/rings/ endpoint is not actually implemented, and added logic to correct placeholder paths in site.json so that ring JSON files can be found. These fixes were necessary before any data-dependent behaviour could even be exercised, indicating that the repository is not even in a workable state

The main blocker then emerged at the ring/database layer. All ring JSON files we inspected have empty connectionString fields, and the README points to a satyrn-rings resource that now returns a 404, so there is no ready-made ring plus database bundle or clear, working configuration that corresponds to the paper’s experiments. The repository does include *-dump.sql files in data/ which appear to be PostgreSQL dumps, implying that each ring is expected to point at a PostgreSQL database restored from these dumps, but there is no end-to-end, tested documentation for how to instantiate these databases, wire them into the ring configs, and obtain a set of valid rings. We therefore created our own helper infrastructure, including a setup_databases.sh script to automate restoring the dumps and updating connection strings, but this is effectively reconstructing missing artifacts and documentation rather than following a provided, canonical setup.

As a result, although we can import and initialize the Satyrn Flask app, inspect ring metadata, and verify that the high-level architectural components are wired together, we cannot obtain a working, data-backed ring configuration that allows SQR analysis or report generation to run over real databases. Without such a configuration, the core experimental pipeline of the paper (running analytics over rings, generating factual statements, producing LLM reports, and recomputing factual/refuted/confabulated claim rates and UniEval scores) cannot be executed as described. Because this failure is driven by missing artifacts (no accessible satyrn-rings resource, empty connection strings, undocumented database setup) and code/API inconsistencies in the released repository, we exclude Satyrn from the set of fully reproduced systems and treat it only as an architecture-level validation rather than a faithful reproduction of the paper’s quantitative results.

title: Fast relational learning using bottom clause propositionalization with artificial neural networks
author: Franca, Manoel V. M. and Gerson, Zaverucha and d'Avila, Garcez Artur S.
abstract: Relational learning can be described as the task of learning first-order logic rules from examples. It has enabled a number of new machine learning applications, e.g. graph mining and link analysis. Inductive Logic Programming (ILP) performs relational learning either directly by manipulating first-order rules or through propositionalization, which translates the relational task into an attribute-value learning task by representing subsets of relations as features. In this paper, we introduce a fast method and system for relational learning based on a novel propositionalization called Bottom Clause Propositionalization (BCP). Bottom clauses are boundaries in the hypothesis search space used by ILP systems Progol and Aleph. Bottom clauses carry semantic meaning and can be mapped directly onto numerical vectors, simplifying the feature extraction process. We have integrated BCP with a well-known neural-symbolic system, C-(ILP)-P-2, to perform learning from numerical vectors. C-(ILP)-P-2 uses background knowledge in the form of propositional logic programs to build a neural network. The integrated system, which we call CILP++, handles first-order logic knowledge and is available for download from Sourceforge. We have evaluated CILP++ on seven ILP datasets, comparing results with Aleph and a well-known propositionalization method, RSD. The results show that CILP++ can achieve accuracy comparable to Aleph, while being generally faster, BCP achieved statistically significant improvement in accuracy in comparison with RSD when running with a neural network, but BCP and RSD perform similarly when running with C4.5. We have also extended CILP++ to include a statistical feature selection method, mRMR, with preliminary results indicating that a reduction of more than 90 % of features can be achieved with a small loss of accuracy.

note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: Towards Reliable Proof Generation with LLMs: ANeuro-Symbolic Approach
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: Large language models (LLMs) struggle with formal domains that require rigorous logical deduction and symbolic reasoning, such as mathematical proof generation. Authors propose a neurosymbolic approach that combines LLMs’ generative strengths with structured components to overcome this challenge.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
We attempted to recreate the authors’ environment from the provided environment.yml, but the file turned out to be an architecture-specific lockfile for macOS/ARM (e.g., python=3.10.14=h2469fbe_0_cpython, xz=5.2.6=h57fd34a_0, etc.). These builds do not exist for linux-64, causing conda env create to fail with PackagesNotFoundError for multiple core libraries. Because the file pins low-level, platform-specific builds instead of giving a portable environment specification, it cannot be used as-is on a standard Linux cluster and would require substantial manual guesswork and re-engineering (stripping out system packages, relaxing pins, and reconstructing the environment by trial and error).

We are therefore excluding this work from our reproducibility study. The environment file is non-portable and effectively unusable outside the authors’ original machine, and there is a severe lack of documentation on how to set up a cross-platform environment, what minimal dependencies are required, and how to run the code end-to-end without relying on this Mac-specific lockfile. Any attempt to “fix” the environment would be speculative and could materially change behavior, so we cannot claim a faithful reproduction under rigorous standards.

title: Complex Program Induction for Querying Knowledge Bases in the Absence of Gold Programs
note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: Complex Program Induction for Querying Knowledge Bases in the Absence of Gold Programs
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: Present Complex Imperative Program Induction from Terminal Rewards (CIPITR), an advanced neural programmer that mitigates reward sparsity with auxiliary rewards, and restricts the program space to semantically correct programs using high-level constraints, KB schema, and inferred answer type.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
MALFORMED / BROKEN ARTIFACTS:
The CITIPR framework released software environment is fundamentally unrecoverable. Both environment files provided in the repository (the TensorFlow requirements and the PyTorch requirements) are not genuine dependency specifications but corrupted exports of an old workstation environment. These files contain mutually contradictory package constraints, including Python-2-only modules mixed with Python-3-only modules, obsolete package pins whose wheels no longer exist, and hard failures such as the requirement to install conda==4.5.11 through pip, which has never been possible. Even after cleaning obvious errors, the environment fails to resolve because many pinned versions are from incompatible eras of TensorFlow, TensorBoard, CUDA, and PyTorch.

The TensorFlow environment file explicitly demands the installation of functools32, a Python-2-exclusive backport that aborts immediately under any Python-3 interpreter. Simultaneously, the same file pins TensorFlow 1.x and associated libraries that do not support Python 2 in the specified versions, meaning no version of Python can satisfy the full set of constraints. The PyTorch environment file exhibits identical defects and includes both CPU and GPU TensorFlow packages, conflicting versions of TensorBoard, and legacy deep-learning dependencies that cannot be installed together on modern systems due to missing wheels and abandoned builds.

These failures are structural, not incidental. The environment specs cannot be cleaned or repaired without effectively rewriting the entire dependency tree, which violates the principle of faithful reproduction. Since the authors did not provide a valid environment specification, and no version of Python or pip can install the dependencies as pinned, the artifacts required to execute the codebase are broken beyond feasible recovery.

The repository hard-codes calls to openai.ChatCompletion.create(...) throughout the reasoning pipeline, and all higher-level components ( including semantic prompting, backoff logic, and tenacity-wrapped inference) are built around this obsolete interface. Because the modern OpenAI client no longer contains these methods, every invocation triggers immediate failures and infinite retry loops. This makes the pipeline non-functional under any currently supported OpenAI Python version.

Attempts to manually patch or modernize the code are not viable, because the breakage propagates deeply through the architecture. Updating the SDK requires substantial refactoring across models/utils.py, SemanticPrompting.py, logic_reasoning.py, and all modules that construct or parse ChatCompletion messages. The code is brittle, heavily intertwined, and relies on undocumented or outdated assumptions about response objects, message formats, and API semantics that no longer exist. Even incremental fixes produce cascading errors, demonstrating that the provided artifacts are not robust to API migration and cannot be repaired without re-engineering core system behavior.

Not being able to reproduce this work due to its dependency on the outdated OpenAI dependence shows the fundamental brittleness of frameworks that have relied solely on API calls.

The FIT codebase, as released, contains a hard import error in QG_FIT.py (from fol import ..., exConEstimator) where exConEstimator does not exist anywhere in the repository. There is no corresponding implementation file (e.g., estimator_exConE.py), no class definition, and no export in fol/__init__.py. This is not a configuration quirk or a missing optional dependency; it is a direct reference to a non-existent symbol.

Because Python resolves all imports at module import time, this missing exConEstimator causes every attempt to import QG_FIT.py to fail immediately, even though the exConE code path is dead (no config uses embedding: exConE). That means all scripts that rely on QG_FIT.py (including the official training and evaluation entrypoints needed to reproduce the paper’s results) are non-executable in the released state. There is no code path that avoids this import; the failure occurs before any runtime logic or configuration choice can kick in.

This is a code integrity problem in the released artifact, not a missing external dataset or a tunable environment mismatch. The repository is internally inconsistent: it declares functionality (exConEstimator / exConE) that is neither implemented nor cleanly excluded. Under a strict reproducibility standard where we are not allowed to patch or rewrite the core research code, this means the primary artifact (the FIT implementation) is malformed: it cannot be run as published.

excel_data.What are the key findings of the study (:
A full end-to-end neuro-symbolic pipeline can map English text through a neural UD parser into extended FOL with defaults and confidences, and then use a high-performance default-logic reasoner to answer questions and generate human-readable explanations.

The system achieves strong performance on an adversarial NLI benchmark (≈95% accuracy on HANS, with errors mainly due to UD parse errors) and solves almost all of the AllenAI ProofWriter demo examples.

The pipeline is robust to distractor sentences in the input where LLMs like GPT can fail, illustrating complementary strengths of symbolic reasoning relative to end-to-end LLMs.

Large integrated commonsense knowledge bases can be leveraged by a theorem prover, but scaling to very large KBs causes combinatorial explosion in proof search, pointing to open research problems in efficiency.
excel_data.Author‑reported limitations:
Performance is described as “miserable” on most standard NLI/QA benchmarks oriented toward machine learning systems.

The system’s performance on HANS is limited by errors from the Stanza UD parser.

Reasoning with very large (~1GB) knowledge bases causes search-space explosion, leading to timeouts and scalability issues.

The implementation is a research prototype, not optimized for broad coverage or high-throughput production deployment.
excel_data.Reviewer‑identified limitations / threat:
Evaluation is focused on a curated subset of tasks (HANS, ProofWriter demos, and synthetic examples) without broad comparisons to many modern NSAI baselines.

The neural component (Stanza) is treated as a black box; the impact of different parser versions is acknowledged but not systematically explored.

ESTIMATED DEBUGGING EFFORT: 
Would require 10-20+ hours to:
1. Regenerate/validate all data files
2. Fix label preprocessing pipeline
3. Debug neural network tensor shapes
4. Create working configurations
5. Document proper setup procedure

VERDICT: Repository is not in a reproducible state. The paper's claims cannot be verified without extensive code repair by authors.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
This paper fails basic reproducibility standards due to multiple severe bugs that prevent any code execution. The repository appears to contain experimental/development code that was never validated for public release.

The most critical blocking issue is corrupted data labels where label values (0-9) exceed the declared class count (3), suggesting data files are from a different experiment version or preprocessing failed entirely. This cannot be resolved without author intervention to provide correct data. Additionally, there is a fundamental type mismatch where the schema declares integer IDs but data contains string IDs with hyphens (e.g., "kristen-1961"), which broke on the first database query and indicates the code was never tested with the provided data files.

The dependency documentation is severely lacking. The code requires Gurobi, a commercial solver costing approximately $2400/year for academic licenses, but this is not clearly documented. While an AD3 alternative exists in the code, there are no instructions on how to use it, making setup impossible for independent researchers. Furthermore, the provided configurations have GPU hardcoded despite CPU support existing, the weighted loss implementation is broken with tensor shape mismatches, and no validated example configuration is provided.

Before this work can be considered reproducible, authors must validate and fix the data files, provide at least one working example configuration that has been fully tested, document the complete setup procedure with step-by-step installation and execution instructions, clarify the Gurobi versus AD3 dependency choice with working examples for both, add data validation and sanity checks to catch type and label mismatches early, and test the entire setup in a clean environment using Docker or conda to verify it works from scratch.

Without author fixes, achieving reproducibility would require an estimated 20+ hours of deep debugging to regenerate data files, fix the label preprocessing pipeline, debug neural network tensor shapes, create working configurations, and document proper setup procedures. With proper author fixes and documentation, setup time could be reduced to 1-2 hours. This situation is particularly problematic because this EMNLP 2022 System Demonstration paper has been cited by others, the DRaiL framework has been used in subsequent publications, and researchers attempting to build on this work will face the same barriers, ultimately undermining trust in publicly released research software.

The reproduction attempt should be rejected with a strong recommendation to contact the authors about providing corrected data files, creating validated setup documentation, and testing the code in a clean environment before claiming public availability. While the conceptual contributions may be sound, the released implementation is not usable by the research community in its current state and does not meet the standards expected for reproducible research software.

excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
We attempted to reproduce the results from this NeurIPS 2024 paper on the Zaratan HPC cluster. We successfully cloned the GitHub repository, verified it corresponds to the paper, and found that all datasets (Active-Logical and SCAN) are included and properly structured. We established the computational environment by creating a conda environment with Python 3.8, installing PyTorch 2.4.1 with CUDA 12.3.0 support, and all required dependencies including PyTorch Geometric, wandb, nltk, and numpy. After resolving a version conflict between torch, torchvision, and torchaudio, we confirmed all packages import correctly and CUDA is detected. The codebase itself is functional and the repository structure appears complete with all necessary scripts.

However, we must reject this submission because the repository lacks trained model checkpoints required for reproducing the paper's reported results. The README provides a command for SCAN evaluation that explicitly uses the flag "test_most_recent_checkpoint=1", indicating it expects pre-existing trained models. We conducted a thorough search of the repository for checkpoint files with extensions like .pt or .pth and found none. Without these artifacts, reproducing the specific quantitative metrics reported in the paper is not possible through evaluation alone. Additionally, the repository provides no specification of expected metric values, random seeds for deterministic reproduction, or hardware requirements. The documentation is misleading as it labels commands as "test commands" for evaluation when no checkpoints exist to test against. For this work to meet reproducibility standards, the authors must provide trained model checkpoints, separate training from evaluation documentation, specify expected results with tolerance ranges, and document all implementation details including random seeds and exact library versions.

excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: The paper presents NeST, a transpiler that converts Sum-Product Loop Programming Language (SPLL) code into executable Python/Julia code for probabilistic inference in neuro-symbolic programs. The tool aims to bridge symbolic programming with neural networks by compiling high-level probabilistic programs into differentiable code for inference and learning.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
This paper is not reproducible due to missing experimental evaluation infrastructure in the associated GitHub repository (https://github.com/vektordev/haskell-dppl).

The repository contains only the core transpiler implementation with 39 basic syntax test cases demonstrating language features. However, it completely lacks the experimental evaluation code necessary to reproduce the quantitative results and metrics reported in the paper. Specifically, the following critical components are missing: (1) no experiments, benchmarks, or evaluation directories; (2) no evaluation scripts or automation for running experiments; (3) no datasets or data processing pipelines; (4) no trained neural network models or model artifacts; (5) no documentation on how to reproduce paper results; and (6) no instructions for setting up experimental environments.

A comprehensive search of the repository including all branches and commit history revealed only development-related commits focused on bug fixes and feature additions to the transpiler itself. Even a commit titled "Experiments and fixes for submission" from February 2022 contained only code refactoring and a trivial test program, not actual experimental evaluation infrastructure.

The README file provides clear instructions for using the transpiler tool to compile SPLL programs into Python or Julia code, but makes no mention of experiments, benchmarks, or how to reproduce any quantitative claims from the paper. The test cases included are purely syntactic examples demonstrating language constructs like conditionals, loops, and probabilistic distributions, not the experimental scenarios evaluated in the paper.

Sevre lack of documentation and lack of dependency / environmental informaiton! 

Excluded due to fundamentally broken architecture / environment dependencies.
We attempted to reproduce CaRing following the authors’ README (Python 3.9, PyTorch 2.0.1 + CUDA 11.8, vllm==0.2.1.post1). In practice, this stack is internally incompatible and fails before any experiments can be run. Specifically, vLLM 0.2.1.post1 contains a known bug where it attempts to set torch.bfloat16 as the global default dtype, which is not supported by PyTorch 2.0.1 and causes hard crashes in model_loader._set_default_torch_dtype. In addition, vLLM 0.2.1.post1 has undocumented tight coupling to Ray internals (e.g. ray.air.util.torch_dist) and to NumPy 1.x ABI; with current Ray and NumPy 2.x, it raises import and binary compatibility errors. The repository’s requirements.txt pins outdated vLLM and torch versions but leaves Ray and NumPy unpinned, so a straightforward installation (even when matching the documented torch/CUDA versions) produces a broken environment.

Recovering a runnable setup would require non-trivial patching or forking of vLLM (to fix the dtype handling and Ray/NumPy assumptions) or a full downgrade to an unmaintained 2023 dependency stack, beyond what we consider reasonable for a reproducibility study. Because the failures are rooted in the released architecture’s dependency design rather than in minor configuration issues, we classify this paper as non-reproducible under realistic modern environments and exclude it from our survey.

title: Perspective Plane Program Induction from a Single Image
note: Extracted from Excel only (no match in include.json)

excel_data.Paper Title: Perspective Plane Program Induction from a Single Image
excel_data.Your Brief Summary on the paper \n(in 1-: proposed framework, Perspective Plane Program Induction (P3I), combines search-based and gradient-based algorithms to efficiently solve the problem. P3I outperforms a set of baselines on a collection of Internet images, across tasks including camera pose estimation, global structure inference, and down-stream image manipulation tasks.
excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
MISSING ARTIFACTS:
This paper relies critically on (1) the NRPP (Nearly-Regular Patterns with Perspective) dataset, consisting of ~64 Internet images of man-made nearly-regular patterns (lattices, circular arrangements, etc.) together with human-annotated camera poses and 2D object-location annotations (e.g., centers of repeated elements), and (2) the PG-IM / Neural Painting Network (NPN) implementation and weights used for the program-guided image-manipulation pipeline (inpainting/extrapolation/regularity editing). While the GitHub repository does provide a pre-trained ImageNet CNN checkpoint (AlexNet-style) used solely as a generic feature extractor, this is not the only required model artifact: the PG-IM/NPN models that actually perform the pixel-level manipulations are not included or linked, and we found no public code or weights for them. Likewise, despite extensive searching, the NRPP dataset (images plus their camera-pose and object-location annotations) is not available as a public download from the paper, the authors’ sites, the project pages, or any standard data host, and no equivalent public mirror could be identified. Because all reported quantitative results (camera pose estimation, repeated pattern detection, and inpainting metrics) are evaluated on NRPP, and all image-manipulation demonstrations depend on the unavailable PG-IM/NPN models, we cannot independently recompute the key metrics or reproduce the main qualitative demos under a “public artifacts only” reproducibility standard. As a result, the core empirical claims of the paper are not verifiable from public resources.

excel_data.If exclude, provide reason: the reported results were not reproduceable
excel_data.Comments on reproduction / Action items:
BUG / MALFORMED CODE:

We cannot reproduce the paper’s results because a blocking defect exists in the WebQA architecture’s parsing pipeline. During parsing, an IndexError: list index out of range is raised from parser_lib/preprocess/table.py, as shown by the stack run_parsing.py → parser_lib/benchmarks.py → parser_lib/scraper.py → parser_lib/preprocess/preprocess.py → parser_lib/preprocess/table.py. The failure occurs in remove_tables() when tables have column headers and many blank rows: the code first builds a headers list aligned with table_rows, then shortens table_rows during blank-row compaction without updating headers. The final loop indexes headers[idx] while iterating table_rows, so idx can exceed len(headers) − 1, triggering the exception.

Because this error happens before parsed artifacts are produced under benchmarks/*/parsed/, the full pipeline cannot proceed to synthesis or evaluation. Skipping the offending pages would yield an incomplete, biased evaluation and invalidate parity with the paper. Consequently, the repository in its current state could not have produced the reported experimental results unless a different (patched) parser was used. Full reproduction requires an upstream fix to parser_lib/preprocess/table.py (e.g., rebuild or bound-check headers after table compaction).
